Lucretius' copy must manifestly be even more vague and inconclusive. The t'ruth is that having laid down his general principles of disease and vindicated his philosophy, he seeks now to satisfy his poetical feeling by a powerful and pathetical description which he has plainly left in an unfinished state. He has been imitated in turn by Virgil geor. 111 47 8—566, closely by Ovid met. vn 523—613, by Seneca Oed. llo—201, by Livy more than once, and by others. 1138 φηονέρβεν aestus has no reference I think to Ilaec: Haec ratio is the law of diseases just mentioned, which at this time caused a mortifer aestus, so that Lachmann⁷s objection ‘quis enim has res diversissimas coniungat, baec ratio et mortifer aestus morborum' has no force: in fact the v. is a paraphrase of 1098 eu vis omnis morborum pestilitasque 3 comp. too 1090 ratio quae sit morbis cet: and for the expression 830 vis baec atque aestus Averni.
